text: I like the idea of wanting to give the girl a normal life, but I feel like Chris Evan's perspective in the film is kinda dumb. She isn't gonna be surrounded by, "nontrivial Russian guys for the rest of her life." From what I can gather she'll be going to a gifted school with other gifted students like her. She could have more opportunities for a better future. And who said that going to a gifted kid's school would prevent her from having a childhood? Personally, I would want to take advantage of this opportunity so that my daughter can have a good future.  We might not be seeing the full scope of the situation here, so I'll have to wait to see the movie before any final judgements.

text: I've always been more advanced than kids my age, and I can say that limiting a child's potential is cruelty. I remember I always hated doing what other kids were doing because I already knew it and I wasn't allowed to learn different or advanced things. It's not true what they say about a gifted child not having a normal life. My mom had me skip a grade and I adjusted just fine. Although I could've skipped more, the state didn't allow it because they thought that a child should be with their age group and that it would make the other kids feel like they were "dumber". But looking back, I honestly wish I could've done different things and been enabled to pursue my potential. Gifted children should be nourished, not told that what they know should be kept hidden. I disagree with the plot of this movie because it's honestly so insane. Why can't she use her "giftedness"? Why must she be so limited? To live a "normal" childhood? And what exactly are the benefits of a normal childhood? What does it even mean to have a normal childhood? Isn't it better for her to expand her already implemented knowledge and achieve what few kids can do at her age? I remember my childhood being great, and I was homeschool most of my elementary years. I was glad that my mom helped my mind open to the infinity of wonders this world has to offer. If a child can see all of that, why not help them? Many would argue that they shouldn't be pushed and that it's cruel to "subdue" them to the things that adults are learning, but from what I can tell, she (the little girl) enjoys being pushed. Many gifted kids are often bored and slack off because they find that there is no point in doing the same thing that other students are doing. I remember I was extremely bored and finished in a few minutes what other kids spent two, three, or four days trying to figure out. Honestly, what is wrong in enhancing the potential of a gifted child? They can either lead a bland, normal life that countless of other children have gone through or be introduced to a world that is so intriguing and complicated that it's nearly unimaginable that a child can understand it. That's the way I see it.

text: Things I learnt from watching this trailer:  * I need to go out and buy some Kellogg's Special K cereal and a MacBook.  * It is best for a gifted kid to go to a "normal" school and be a "normal" child and interact with other "normal" children (i.e. fake being average as best she can because "no one likes a smarta**") while sitting in a classroom listening to a teacher telling her stuff she already knows, rather than her going to a school that is specialized in making her realize her potential and where she will meet other gifted kids and be able to interact with them as peers and probably make more friends than she would have in a "normal" school (because around other gifted children, she will actually BE "normal" without having to fake it).  * "You wanted me before I was smart" implies that there was a time in this kid's life when she wasn't. So I assume that means she wasn't born smart but rather drank a magic potion at age 5 and suddenly knew advanced math?

text: This is such BS. If someone is gifted at sports they are sent to special sports schools. The vast majority of sportspeople are left with almost nothing once past their prime, and even less if they get a serious injury before they get their career going. But sending smart kids to schools where they can be among their intellectual equals,  where they can use their full potential is "bad" for them, because "nobody likes a smartass".  I have news for you. I was a smart kid at a normal school, and the other kids didn't like me anyways. I did not learn to apply effort in my studies, and this caused problems for me later in uni. I would have chosen a school with smarter kids any day of the week. It always amazes me how in the US there is such a cult towards success, yet such disdain for "nerds", "smarasses", "elites", "intellectuals". You are steering smart kids towards sports, acting, petty celebrity status, while discouraging them to learn. No surprise so many of your CEOs are immigrants, and immigrants are taking your jobs.

text: This movie does a disservice to every gifted child, it leads their parents down a path that will provide their offspring with nothing but resentment, frustration, a sense of constant disappointment, anxiety and depression for their gifted child.  Being gifted is SO much more than being good with numbers...it is an ENTIRE way a child views EVERYTHING in the world.    Painting gifted schools as a closed-minded 'think-tanks ' that will 'rob' a child of a fulfilling life is a sack of horseshit.  Being surrounded by other children as gifted and as curious about EVERYTHING in the world will complete a gifted child, and provide them with desperately wanted stimulus and reward.  As the father of a young gifted child I live this amazing, frustrating and constantly evolving reality every day...Movies like this place a priority of an emotional response over what is truly right for the child; Chris Evans' character should move to where the school for her daughter is located and give her that stimulus as well as the love she needs from her father.  Please consider  these readings before drinking the emotionally laden Kool-Aid offered by this movie:  http://www.byrdseed.com/five-unexpected-traits-of-gifted-students/  http://www.raisinglifelonglearners.com/overexcitabilities-and-why-they-matter-for-gifted-kids/ http://www.huffingtonpost.com/marianne-kuzujanakis/the-intensities-of-gifted_b_8134926.html

text: I... don't like this. I'm not a smart person. I wish I was. I don't know if anything is for certain or if nothing is.   All I'll say is this.   Stories that paint pictures with absolutes are already suspect.  I've known smart people who have taken advantage of their gifts.   And I've know those who've squandered it.  You can have a normal childhood and become president, or a doctor, or an astronaut.  You can have a normal childhood and become homeless, a drug addict, a criminal.  You can have a normal childhood and become a bank teller, a nurse, a mechanic, or a math tutor.   Please don't take anything away from this movie. Except that it is.

text: So this frustrates me.  I had a son who was easily doing algebra and reading at an 8th grade level by the time he was 4. He somehow figured it all out on his own - easily flying through an on line math course at his own choosing. I had a very difficult time educating him because his teachers couldn't keep up and some called his advanced learning ability a problem for the rest of the class.  We bounced from school to school - private schools turned him away because they could.  I got him a math tutor at Dartmouth when he was 7 - he was in high school at 9 - thanks to the principal who had her PHD in profoundly gifted education - he was the captain of the high school Latin team at 11 (and he loved it and they him)  - but still was a kid - still had a childhood - still had friends his own age. Finished with college at 18 (although it would have been sooner if I let him finish high school at 14) ... Why do people think that just because a kid is a fast learner.... and gets to keep up with what he wants to learn - that robs him of his childhood.  That mind needs stimulation - encouragement for learning... He is now 30 and completely normal and happy.

text: Who does not desire their children to be "uber" - to be exceptionally intelligent, and see more than others their own age?  But history shows that it is extremely rare for mathematically talented parents to sire mathematically brilliant children.  It is as if math cannot be taught, but I suspect otherwise.  I suspect "tiger moms" have the 'secret recipe', but historically, unlike politics or business, one simply does not see a family of nobel prize winners, such as the Royal Tannenbaums (Ben Stiller).  It is a myth.    Godliness?  Well, you can give a child instruction as to the way he should go, but if he has no desire to learn.. And so the brothers and sisters of Noah did not make it into the Ark.     If they refuse to learn, should you not seek others who will?  Or continue growing, alone and apart?  ...  The prophet Elijah spent much time on a mountain, and in a cave.  "It's lonely at the top" ?
